This paper deals with interpretability in Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and proposes a method for scoring superpixels using gradient-based pixel scoring techniques. This is particularly relevant in computer vision tasks such as image classification and action recognition, which fall under the sub-category of Computer Vision (cs.CV). The paper also discusses the trade-off between efficiency and interpretability, which is a common concern in Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the use of large-scale datasets such as ImageNet and Kinetics-400 suggests that this paper may also fall under Multimedia (cs.MM) and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-categories.
